    {
      "_id": "19",
      "role": "volunteer",
      "content": "it's an altitude. The thing about isosceles triangles is that because the two sides are equal, there's only one line that can be an altitude, and that line is the perpendicular bisector. Not only does the perpendicular bisector make a right angle, it also splits the top angle (BAD in this case) in half and splits the base in half as well",
      "start_time": "",
      "end_time": "",
      "timestamp": "",
      "session_id": "",
      "sequence_id": "19",
      "annotations": []
    },
    {
      "_id": "20",
      "role": "volunteer",
      "content": "so because AC is an altitude, C is also the midpoint of BD, meaning CB and DC have the same length",
      "start_time": "",
      "end_time": "",
      "timestamp": "",
      "session_id": "",
      "sequence_id": "20",
      "annotations": []
